onal name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Catherine Harcourt was born about 1370, in Oxfordshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Ranulph Mainwaring. She died in 1390, in Over Peover, Cheshire, England, at the age of 21."},"et":{"about 1370–1390":"umbes 1370–1390","1363–1456":"1363–1456","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1370–1390":"1370–1390","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1456":"1456","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","1382":"1382","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Over-Peover, Cheshire":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1370–1390":"noin 1370–1390","1363–1456":"1363–1456","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1370–1390":"1370–1390","about 1370":"noin 1370","1456":"1456","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","1382":"1382","about 1385":"noin 1385","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","Over-Peover, Cheshire":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1370–1390":"environ 1370–1390","1363–1456":"1363–1456","1385–1